Let $B_{p,q}^s(\mathbb{R}^n)$ denote the Besov space with parameters $p,q,s$, where $1\leq p,q\leq \infty$ and $s\in \mathbb{R}$. Let $w:\mathbb{R}^n\to\mathbb{R}$ be a weight, i.e., a non-negative measurable function. The Lorentz space $L_{p,q}(w)$ is defined as the set of measurable functions $f$ on $\mathbb{R}^n$ such that
\begin{align*}
\|f\|_{L_{p,q}(w)}:=\Big(\int_0^\infty \Big(t^{1/p}\|f\chi_{\{ |f|>t\}}\|_{L^p(w)}\Big)^q\,\frac{dt}{t}\Big)^{1/q},
\end{align*}
if $1\leq q<\infty$, and
\begin{align*}
\|f\|_{L_{p,\infty}(w)}:=\sup_{t>0}\Big(t^{1/p}\|f\chi_{\{ |f|>t\}}\|_{L^p(w)}\Big).
\end{align*}
It is known that if $w\in A_p$ (with the Muckenhoupt class $A_p$ defined as the set of weights $w$ such that $(w)_{p'}\leq K(w)_p$ for some $1<p<\infty$, where $(w)_{p'}$ and $K(w)_p$ are the weak and strong Muckenhoupt constants, respectively), then for $1\leq p<\infty$ and $1\leq q\leq \infty$ there exists a positive constant $C$ such that for all $s\in \mathbb{R}$ we have
\begin{align*}
\|f\|_{L_{p,q}(w)}\leq C\|f\|_{B_{p,q}^s}.
\end{align*} 
This embedding of Besov spaces into Lorentz spaces is an extension of the standard embedding of Besov spaces into Lebesgue spaces. The Lorentz spaces provide a more flexible setting for studying the regularity of functions than Lebesgue spaces, as they incorporate both the local and global behavior of functions and are well-suited for studying weighted estimates.

